The first controversy surrounding a Bush cabinet nominee has erupted during the confirmation 
hearings of former Senator John Tower as Secretary of Defense. In testimony before the Senate 
Armed Services Committee, Paul Weyrich told the committee that Tower may lack the moral 
fiber for the position, citing inappropriate use of alcohol and questionable associations with 
women. Criticism from Weyrich and other witnesses has caused some committee members to 
rethink their position on the nomination. Committee chairman Sam Nunn, of the other hand 
commented that there has been a surplus of rumor and a shortage of personal knowledge.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d118"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910213-0136"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="E">

The nomination of John Tower as Secretary of Defense failed in the Senate as Tower fell victim 
to charges of moral and ethical misbehavior. Tower insisted that Senator Nunn used FBI inquiries 
to discredit him and to strike at the president of the United States. Tower was qualified for the 
job, having himself served as chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee. Tower's 
intelligence and patriotism were never in question and it came as a surprise to him that he had 
made many enemies in Washington. Allegations from conservative groups as well as Tower's 
second wife fed the rumors surrounding him.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d118"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890309-0143"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="E">

The Senate voted 53 to 47 to reject the nomination of former Texas Senator John tower as 
Secretary of Defense. The vote came after a bitter and divisive debate which centered on Tower's 
drinking habits, his inappropriate behavior toward women and business dealings with defense 
contractors. This is only the ninth time that a president's cabinet choice has been rejected and the 
first time it has occurred so early in a new administration. The defeat was credited to the decision 
by Senator Sam Nun, Chairman of the Armed Services Committee, to oppose him. Nunn's 
decision caused the other Democrats on the committee to fall in line behind him.</SUM>

