A Senate Armed Services committee vote to approve former Senator John Tower as Secretary of 
Defense was cancelled Thursday following allegations of recent drinking problems as will as 
inappropriate behavior with women. The FBI is looking into the matter and the results of their 
investigation are not expected until Tuesday. Tower stated that he limited his drinking to an 
occasional glass of wine. Staff members also reported that recently he has been ordering only 
tonic water with his meals. Tower's work with defense contractors also raised questions with the 
committee but did not appear to threaten his nomination.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d118"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890105-0224"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="E">

Former Senator John Tower, President Bush's nominee as defense secretary under went surgery 
to remove a colon polyp on Thursday. Senator Tower was listed in fair condition following the 
surgery and is expected to make a full recovery. Tower entered the hospital on Wednesday after a 
colonoscopy revealed the polyp. A preliminary biopsy of the polyp, which was removed during a 
three hour surgery, showed it to be benign. A rectal polyp was removed during the colonoscopy 
which showed malignant but well differentiated cells. An announcement on the first polyp was to 
come from Tower's surgeon on Thursday.</SUM> 


